{{EngvarB|date=December 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}} {{Infobox person |name = Margaret Anne Ganley Somerville |image = |alt = |caption = |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1942|04|13}} |birth_place = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]] |death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=y|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |death_place = |other_names = |known_for = |occupation = Ethicist |nationality = }}
'''Margaret Anne Ganley Somerville''', {{Post-nominals|country=AUS|AM}} {{Post-nominals|FRSC}} (born 13 April 1942) is Professor of Bioethics at [[University of Notre Dame Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nd.edu.au/news/media-releases/2016/091 | title= Notre Dame welcomes Professor Margaret Somerville |publisher=University of Notre Dame Australia|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> She was previously Samuel Gale Professor of Law at [[McGill University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nd.edu.au/news/media-releases/2016/091 | title= Retirement of our colleagues Paul Dempsey and Margaret Somerville |publisher=University of Notre Dame Australia|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref>
Somerville was born in [[Adelaide]], South Australia, and educated at [[Mercedes College (Adelaide)|Mercedes College]] ([[Springfield, South Australia|Springfield]], South Australia). She received a A.u.A. (pharm.) from the [[University of Adelaide]] in 1963, a [[Bachelor of Law]] degree (Hons. I) and the University Medal from the [[University of Sydney]] in 1973, and a D.C.L. from McGill University in 1978.
In 1978, she was appointed assistant professor in the law faculty at McGill. She was appointed an associate professor in 1979 and an associate professor in the faculty of medicine in 1980. In 1984, she became a full professor in both faculties, and in 1989, she was appointed the Samuel Gale Professor of Law. From 1986 to 1996, she was the founding director of the McGill Centre for Medicine, Ethics and Law and was appointed acting director in 1999.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://archivalcollections.library.mcgill.ca/index.php/margaret-a-somerville-fonds|title=Margaret A. Somerville Fonds|website=McGill Library Archival Catalogue|language=en|access-date=2018-02-01}}</ref> She currently teaches seminars on advanced torts and comparative medical law at McGill. Her archive is held at the McGill University Archives.<ref name=":0" />
In November 2006, she gave the five annual [[Massey Lectures]] on [[CBC Radio]] in Canada. An expanded version of the lectures was published in Canada, Australia, and the United States in book form as ''The Ethical Imagination: Journeys of the Human Spirit''.
==Honours== Among many honours and awards, in 1990, Somerville was made a Member of the [[Order of Australia]] "for service to the law and to bioethics".<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=882353&search_type=quick&showInd=true]</ref> In 1991, she was made a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Canada]]. In 2004 she was chosen by an international jury as the first recipient of [[UNESCO]]'s Avicenna Prize for Ethics in Science.<ref>[http://portal.unesco.org/en/ev.php-URL_ID=20029&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html]</ref>
She has received honorary degrees from [[University of Windsor]] (1992), [[Macquarie University]] (1993), [[St. Francis Xavier University]] (1996) and the [[University of Waterloo]] (2004). Her honorary degree awarded 19 June 2006, at [[Ryerson University]] in Toronto was controversial<ref>http://www.ccrl.ca/index.php?id=331</ref> because of her objections to [[same sex marriage]]. She has since received honorary degrees from [[Mount Saint Vincent University]] in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], Nova Scotia (2009), [[St. Mark's College, Vancouver|St. Mark's College]], Vancouver (2010) and the [[Royal Military College of Canada]] in [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]], Ontario (2013).
In 2006, Somerville was nominated for membership in the [[Order of Canada]] by [[Carol Finlay]], a professor at the [[Toronto School of Theology]]. Finlay says Somerville was turned down for the honour because she was "too controversial."<ref>Aubin, Henry. (2006). ''[http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/features/viewpoints/story.html?id=62cda378-0d93-4a8b-8d88-010af82ffe62 McGill ethicist refused OC because she was 'too controversial'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104155543/http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/features/viewpoints/story.html?id=62cda378-0d93-4a8b-8d88-010af82ffe62 |date=4 November 2012 }}'', The Montreal Gazette, 8 July 2008.</ref>
==Involvement in same-sex marriage debate== Somerville presented both a brief and an oral presentation to the [[Canadian House of Commons Standing Committee on Justice and Human Rights]] opposing the legalisation of same-sex marriage in Canada in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |first=Margaret |last=Somerville |url=http://www.catholiceducation.org/en/controversy/marriage/the-case-against-same-sex-marriage.html |title=The Case Against "Same-sex marriage" |publisher=Catholic Education Resource Center |accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?Pub=CommitteeMeetingEvidence&Acronym=just&Mee=39&Language=e&Mode=1&Parl=37&Ses=2 37th PARLIAMENT, 2nd SESSION Standing Committee on Justice and Human Rights] Parliament of Canada. Retrieved 25 November 2013</ref>
